Understood. Then the answer is:

Yes, you can move to Graviton only, but you must convert/rebuild every Sensu runtime asset to ARM64 first. There is no safe Graviton-only path where AMD64-only assets continue working unchanged.

Sensu itself can run on Linux arm64, but Sensu runtime assets are separate packages used by checks, handlers, mutators, and filters. Sensu selects asset builds using filters like entity.system.arch == 'amd64' or entity.system.arch == 'arm64', so AMD64-only assets will not match ARM64 agents/backends. 

What you should do

Keep:

Existing check names
Existing asset names
Existing runtime_assets references
Existing ArgoCD/GitOps flow

Change:

Asset artifacts: add ARM64 builds
Sensu image: use ARM64/multi-arch image
Kustomize scheduling: force pods to arm64 nodes

Required migration sequence

1. First, inventory all assets

From your STG branch:

grep -R "type: Asset" .
grep -R "runtime_assets" .
grep -R "entity.system.arch" .
grep -R "amd64" .

You need to classify each asset:

Asset type	What to do

Go binary plugin	Rebuild with GOARCH=arm64
Shell-only script	Usually repack same script as ARM64-compatible after testing
Python/Ruby/Node asset	Rebuild/test on ARM64 because dependencies may include native libraries
Vendor/Bonsai asset	Check whether newer version has linux_arm64 build
Closed-source AMD64 binary	Cannot move to Graviton unless vendor provides ARM64 build


2. Rebuild assets for ARM64

For Go-based Sensu plugins:

GOOS=linux GOARCH=arm64 CGO_ENABLED=0 go build -o bin/check-example ./cmd/check-example
tar -czf check-example_linux_arm64.tar.gz bin/check-example
sha512sum check-example_linux_arm64.tar.gz

For shell-only assets, you may be able to reuse the same script package, but still test it on an ARM64 node before adding the arm64 filter.

3. Keep the same asset name, add ARM64 build

Do not rename assets.

Your check can stay like this:

runtime_assets:
  - check-disk

Update the existing asset:

type: Asset
api_version: core/v2
metadata:
  name: check-disk
  namespace: default
spec:
  builds:
    - url: https://artifacts.example.com/check-disk_linux_amd64.tar.gz
      sha512: <amd64-sha512>
      filters:
        - entity.system.os == 'linux'
        - entity.system.arch == 'amd64'

    - url: https://artifacts.example.com/check-disk_linux_arm64.tar.gz
      sha512: <arm64-sha512>
      filters:
        - entity.system.os == 'linux'
        - entity.system.arch == 'arm64'

This lets you keep all existing checks unchanged.

4. Move Sensu to ARM64 only after assets are ready

Once every required asset has ARM64 support, update the Sensu backend and agent scheduling in your STG Kustomize overlay.

Example patch:

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: sensu-backend
spec:
  template:
    spec:
      nodeSelector:
        kubernetes.io/arch: arm64

For the agent DaemonSet:

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: DaemonSet
metadata:
  name: sensu-agent
spec:
  template:
    spec:
      nodeSelector:
        kubernetes.io/arch: arm64

EKS/Graviton scheduling commonly uses the Kubernetes label kubernetes.io/arch: arm64 to force pods onto Graviton nodes. 

If your Graviton nodes are tainted, also add:

tolerations:
  - key: graviton
    operator: Equal
    value: "true"
    effect: NoSchedule

AWS also recommends taints when introducing Graviton nodes so incompatible AMD64 workloads do not accidentally schedule there. 

5. Validate in STG

After ArgoCD sync:

kubectl get nodes -L kubernetes.io/arch
kubectl get pods -n <sensu-namespace> -o wide

Confirm Sensu pods are on ARM64 nodes:

kubectl get pod -n <sensu-namespace> -o custom-columns=NAME:.metadata.name,NODE:.spec.nodeName

Then check Sensu:

sensuctl entity list
sensuctl asset list --format yaml
sensuctl check list
sensuctl event list

Look specifically for asset download or execution errors in agent/backend logs:

kubectl logs -n <sensu-namespace> daemonset/sensu-agent
kubectl logs -n <sensu-namespace> deploy/sensu-backend

Important: do not rely on AMD64 emulation

Technically, people sometimes try QEMU/binfmt emulation for AMD64 binaries on ARM64 nodes, but I would not recommend it for Sensu checks in production. It adds performance overhead, debugging complexity, and weakens the cost-saving reason for moving to Graviton.

Final recommendation

For Graviton only, your minimum required checklist is:

1. Use ARM64/multi-arch Sensu backend/agent image.
2. Rebuild or replace every Sensu runtime asset for ARM64.
3. Keep check definitions unchanged.
4. Keep asset names unchanged.
5. Add arm64 builds under the existing Asset resources.
6. Force backend and agent pods to kubernetes.io/arch: arm64.
7. Validate all checks, handlers, mutators, and events in STG.

So yes, you can move fully to Graviton, but the blocking work is asset conversion, not Sensu check migration.